{
  "answer": "Several texts in the corpus speak directly to the reader (or practitioner/addressee) in the second person:\n\n1. **Fichte — Zurückforderung der Denkfreiheit (both chapters)**: The most explicit and sustained second-person address to the reader. The author directly harangues 'you peoples' and 'you princes' throughout: 'No, you peoples, give up everything, everything, but not freedom of thought'; 'do not hate your princes; you should hate yourselves'; 'The times of barbarism are over, you peoples…' (ch. 2). (work_slug: johann-gottlieb-fichte-zuruckforderung-der-denkfreiheit-bookde, chapters 1–2)\n\n2. **Iqbal — Bang-E-Dara Part 3, ch. 13 (Khitab ba Jawanan-e-Islam / Address to the Muslim Youth)**: Explicitly titled 'An Address to the Muslim Youth' and sustains a direct second-person address throughout: 'Have you ever, O Muslim youth, paused for solemn reflection? / What was that firmament, of which you are but a shattered star?' (work_slug: allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8, chapter 13)\n\n3. **Iqbal — Bang-E-Dara Part 3, ch. 4 (Dil se jo baat nikalti hai)**: Addresses the Muslim community directly in the second person: 'You are the ones who have no worldly art; / You are the folk who do not care to start / To build a nest…' (work_slug: allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8, chapter 4)\n\n4. **Old English Elegies, ch. 15 (Wilt thu, fus haele)**: The narrator directly addresses the reader: 'Learn now this lore. I shall swiftly tell you / of the Measurer's might…' and 'Hear now this song of praise and make firm your thought.' (work_slug: unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e, chapter 15)\n\n5. **Old English Elegies, ch. 6 (Maxims I)**: Opens with a direct second-person address: 'Question me with wise words! Do not let your spirit be hidden, / nor conceal what you know most deeply. / I will not tell you my secrets, if you hide from me your mind's craft.' (work_slug: unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e, chapter 6)\n\nThe following Kawi (Old Javanese) instructional/theological texts also speak directly to the disciple/practitioner in sustained second-person throughout their translations — the practitioner is the textual addressee:\n\n6. **San Hyan Kamahayanikan** (ch. 1): 'you must know the ultimate secret'; 'Be at ease in your mind'; 'you are the body of a Divine Buddha this very instant'. (work_slug: unknown-san-hyan-kamahayanikan-2a0c19)\n\n7. **San Hyan Mahajnana** (ch. 1): 'You must know this, O revered Kumāra'; 'you are the one, my son, Kumāra'. (work_slug: unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531)\n\n8. **Vrhaspatitattva** (ch. 1): 'the kinds of tattva you must know'; 'Here are their characteristics, which I will explain to you'. (work_slug: unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28)\n\n9. **Ganapatitattva** (ch. 1): 'My son, Gaṇapati, listen now to my teachings to you'; 'which you must know, my son, Gaṇapati'. (work_slug: unknown-ganapatitattva-66a136)\n\n10. **Kunjarakarna Dharmakathana** (ch. 1): 'Be diligent in listening to my instruction, do not take it lightly. For now you will find the fruit of my words'. (work_slug: unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a)\n\n11. **Vratisasana** (ch. 1): 'The mind of equanimity, that is what you must have as your mind, O viku'. (work_slug: unknown-vratisasana-d0fe75)\n\nNote: Many Iqbal poems address non-reader entities (Sun, Candle, Sicily) in second person — these are apostrophes to subjects, not direct address to the reader. Similarly, Old English Elegies ch. 17 depicts a father addressing his son in second person, but that is dialogue within the narrative.",
